{
  "texts": [
    "8 Davidson's own views about these matters are significantly complicated by his denial that statements of the causal laws governing physical event causation can be integrated with a prospective science of human behaviour.",
    "This is a major part of the motivation for his 'anomalous monism' but does not cause him to reject the claim that action explanation, cast in ordinary folk-psychological terms, is causal.",
    "Moreover, the standard story has been taken up by philosophers who reject these further Davidsonian claims; whether or not they really are integral to it, we can plausibly make progress while shelving the argument about anomalous monism for the moment.",
    "9 The term 'basic action' is due to Danto (1965) and is not used by Davidson in the early essays that set out his notion of agential basicness.",
    "Nonetheless, the term has since become standard in the literature with more-or-less the sense I'm giving to it (Aguilar & Buckareff 2010)."
  ]
}